Why we need Simon, Gabrielle, and Laurie
This was how I evaluated the women's Olympic gymnastic team, and there is more than one reason for it.
Firstly, I have attended every Summer Olympics since 1984, and the United States has never dominated the sport as they did today.
This team of gymnasts include 3 excellent athletes: Simone Biles, Gabby Douglas, and Lauren “Laurie” Hernandez who have inspired many girls of color.
The composition of the team is something that everyone can be proud of. It includes Aly Raisman, a Jew, and Madison Kocian, a Catholic.
This team is finally starting to look like an American team.
It also strengthened the leading position of African and Latin American women in this sport.
For the last four years, the best female gymnast in the US has been an African American.
Last year, Simone and Gabrielle were ranked first and second.
That was awesome.
In the previous Olympics, Gabrielle Douglas “surprisingly” became the Olympics champion, a feat that got America cheering.
Today, the world can witness the exciting performances of three-time world champions, Simone Biles, Gabby Douglas and Laurie Hernandez. They have elevated conventional gymnastic techniques to the highest level of artistic interpretation.
On Thursday, Simone helped the US team achieve four consecutive championships in the women’s individual all-around event.
Her teammate Aly Raisman won the silver medal.
We have ascended the zenith of this sport, but gymnastic classes throughout the entirety of the United States are not like this.
The journey that took Simon, Gabby, and Laurie into the Olympics team was similar to that experienced by Ali and Madison.
They will be the “Final Five” as the next Olympic gymnastics team will be composed of 4 athletes. This is the last year in which Marta Karolyi will be serving as the coach.
The truth is that gymnastics is an expensive sport. Gymnasts are mainly trained in private gymnastic clubs. Their parents must pay for expenses that include training, facilities, traveling, clothing, competition fees, and accommodation (including relevant expenses for the coach, gymnasts, and family members). The list of expenses is still growing.
Most sports clubs are situated in affluent neighborhoods that can provide support for this industry.
All the training of gymnasts was conducted at these clubs, which was a long-term and considerable expense for the families of gymnasts.
Aimee Boorman, Biles’ coach, and Maggie Haney, the coach of Hernandez, have coached the two gymnasts since they began training in gymnastics.
We must provide more practical and accessible gymnastic training to young girls who have been influenced by Simon, Gabrielle, and Laurie.
I founded my own gymnastics foundation 20 years ago.
In my organization, we provide free and affordable gymnastics to more than 15,000 urban youths (mainly Black and Hispanic Americans) in Black neighborhoods, and have nurtured national and even world champions.
We shall expand to Detroit (my hometown) in September to provide quality gymnastics to youths who deserve this learning opportunity and could benefit from this fantastic Olympic sport.
Gymnastics helps develop physical power, flexibility, and coordination. It also helps develop perseverance, self-discipline, and determination.
These can bring lifetime benefits to a person’s health, academic and career success.
Encouraged by this team, many girls will take up gymnastics. This is wonderful.
Participation in sports carries great significance, particularly for girls.
This is an inspiring moment.
We would like to thank Simone, Aly, Laurie, Gabrielle and Madison for their dazzling display of “girl power” enroute to winning the Olympic team gold medal, and we would also like to thank them for inspiring young girls from different backgrounds to unlock their path toward health, strength and success.
