Future of Portland smelter uncertain with cancellation of power supply contract
The power company supply power to the plants disclosed that the owner of the plant will be terminating a supplier contract, an act that would lead to termination of all supplier contracts. The Portland Aluminum Smelter plant in Victoria and hundreds of workers currently face an uncertain future.
This measure was enacted after the government of Victoria decided to stop issuing subsidies that help keep the plants in business.
This 20-year fixed subsidy will end in November.
The 2,000 workers at the Portland plant of Alcoa Corporation may lose their jobs.
Once the factory shuts down, up to 2,000 people may find themselves directly or indirectly out of a job.
As total energy use of this plant makes up 10% of total power output of Victoria, it is unlikely that it would generate a chain reaction.
Alcoa Corporation shut down the Point Henry aluminum plant in 2014, which led to the shutdown of the Anglesey power station last year.
Alcoa’s Portland smelting plant is now loss-making and is at risk of closing down.
This measure was implemented after making predictions on the near future of the factory. The initial reason was the appreciation of the Australian Dollar. The recent reason is the price of the factory products.
AGL made use of the Latrobe Valley Loy Yang power plant to supply electrical power to this large aluminum smelting facility. This company also expects 3 owners of the factory to terminate the contract in the future.
The largest shareholder is a joint venture formed by Alcoa Corporation and Alox Company. CITIC Group from China and Marubeni Corporation from Japan also holds a small percentage of the shares.
The joint venture expressed: “AGL expects the Portland facility to continue operations. In other words, this smelting plant shall continue to demand electrical power.”
AGL said that these contracts were “hedging contracts” that should have become effective on November 2016.
The contract has a termination period of 12 months, and thus will be terminated in 2017.
The power company said, “As such, AGL still predicts these contracts to continue to produce revenue in fiscal year 2017.”
For the fiscal year of 2018, any impact to revenue that may be generated for AGL is currently affected by the optimistic prospects held by the futures market regarding the prices of wholesale electricity.
AGL expressed that the company has down-written a contract value of 187 million USD for “expected event of termination”.
Alcoa said that the decision to terminate the contracts ”does not affect Alcoa’s ability to operate the smelter or secure electricity supply to the smelter”.
This American company expressed that they have signed a 20-year contract with Loy Yang in 2010. This contract was supposed to enter into force in November this year, but this company did not explain why it chose to withdraw.
Analysts remain circumspect with respect to the closure of the Portland Foundry at Victoria and Tomago plant in Newcastle as a result of the bad economy.
According to comments published earlier this week by analysts, AGL’s head of operations Stephen Mikkelsen expressed that annual power consumption of the Portland plant amounted to about 600 megawatt, while that of the Tomago plant was at about 900 megawatt.
If two factories close down, demand in the electricity market will fall significantly.
He expressed that: “As a power company, this is not good news to us.”
Community Legal Centres turn away 160,000 people each year
Every year, over 160,000 of the most underprivileged groups have been denied access to the community legal center. This service is already facing the issue of inadequate funds. Now they must face an additional budget slash.
In Queensland, three in every five persons have been rejected when seeking free legal advice and representation services. Most of these were the elderly, migrants, vulnerable workers, victims of abuse, as well as people without resources opposing unfair expulsion.
The lack of funding for community legal services has long been stretched beyond limit. Now the fund must face additional budget slashes.
From June next year, the federal government will reduce funds provided to these legal centers by another 30%.
James Farrell, Director of Community Legal Centres Queensland, said that according to a National Association of Community Legal Centres survey, thousands are turned away every year.
Mr. Farrell expressed that if the federal government does not change the current decision, this situation will only get worse.
He said, “Queensland’s Community Legal Centers constantly suffers from inadequate funding. This implies that many are unable to receive important services they require.”
People such as those who must seek shelter from violence, who are unable to pay back their large debts, families facing the threat of disintegration, and abused workers face legal issues. This report showed that they were unable to receive the help they need.
With effect from June 2017, the Federal government will cut funding by another 30%, implying that thousands of vulnerable groups in Queensland would be forced to face complex legal issues without any help.
We call upon George Brandis, Attorney-General and senator representing Queensland, to revoke the decision for cutting back investments so that people can acquire the help they need to deal with legal issues.
The state government made a commitment last year to increase the legal aid fund to the national average.
Priority must now be placed on community legal centres and how they correspond to the needs of the community. The Palaszczuk government must also commit to this important task.
